1 (2) Except as provided in 16-6-305, a parent or guardian or any person who is 18 years of age or
2 older, whether or not the parent, guardian, or other person is supervising the welfare of the child, commits the
3 offense of endangering the welfare of children if the parent, guardian, or other person knowingly contributes to
4 the delinquency of a child less than:
5 (a) 18 years old by:
6 (i) supplying or encouraging the use of an intoxicating substance by the child; or
7 (ii) assisting, promoting, or encouraging the child to enter a place of prostitution; or
8 (b) 16 years old by assisting, promoting, or encouraging the child to:
9 (i) abandon the child's place of residence without the consent of the child's parents or guardian; or
10 (ii) engage in sexual conduct.
11 (3) A person, whether or not the person is supervising the welfare of a child less than 18 years of
12 age, commits the offense of endangering the welfare of children if the person, in the residence of a child, in a
13 building, structure, conveyance, or outdoor location where a child might reasonably be expected to be present,
14 in a room offered to the public for overnight accommodation, or in any multiple-unit residential building,
15 knowingly:
16 (a) produces or manufactures methamphetamine, fentanyl, heroin, or cocaine or attempts to
17 produce or manufacture methamphetamine, fentanyl, heroin, or cocaine;
18 (b) possesses any material, compound, mixture, or preparation that contains any combination of
19 the items listed in 45-9-107 with intent to manufacture methamphetamine; or
20 (c) causes or permits a child to inhale, be exposed to, have contact with, or ingest
21 methamphetamine, fentanyl, heroin, or cocaine or be exposed to or have contact with methamphetamine or
22 drug paraphernalia as defined in 45-10-101.
23 (4) A parent, guardian, or other person supervising the welfare of a child less than 16 years of age
24 may verbally or in writing request a person who is 18 years of age or older and who has no legal right of
25 supervision or control over the child to stop contacting the child if the requester believes that the contact is not
26 in the child's best interests. If the person continues to contact the child, the parent, guardian, or other person
27 supervising the welfare of the child may petition or the county attorney may upon the person's request petition
28 for an order of protection under Title 40, chapter 15. To the extent that they are consistent with this subsection,
