1 the provisions of Title 40, chapter 15, apply. A person who purposely or knowingly violates an order of
2 protection commits the offense of endangering the welfare of children and upon conviction shall be sentenced
3 as provided in subsection (5)(a).
4 (5) (a) Except as provided in subsection (5)(b), a person convicted of endangering the welfare of
5 children shall be fined an amount not to exceed $500 or be imprisoned in the county jail for any term not to
6 exceed 6 months, or both. A person convicted of a second offense of endangering the welfare of children shall
7 be fined an amount not to exceed $1,000 or be imprisoned in the county jail for any term not to exceed 6
8 months, or both.
9 (b) A person convicted under subsection (3) is guilty of a felony and shall be imprisoned in the
10 state prison for a term not to exceed 5 years and may be fined an amount not to exceed $10,000, or both. If a
11 child suffers serious bodily injury, the offender shall be fined an amount not to exceed $25,000 or be imprisoned
12 for a term not to exceed 10 years, or both. Prosecution or conviction of a violation of subsection (3) does not
13 bar prosecution or conviction for any other crime committed by the offender as part of the same conduct.
14 (6) On the issue of whether there has been a violation of the duty of care, protection, and support,
15 the following, in addition to all other admissible evidence, is admissible: cruel treatment; abuse; infliction of
16 unnecessary and cruel punishment; abandonment; neglect; lack of proper medical care, clothing, shelter, and
17 food; and evidence of past bodily injury.
18 (7) The court may order, in its discretion, any fine levied or any bond forfeited upon a charge of
19 endangering the welfare of children paid to or for the benefit of the person or persons whose welfare the
20 defendant has endangered."
